The Kenya Private Schools Association has welcomed the proposed new curriculum, saying it will bridge the gap in the labour industry.National vice-chairman Isaiah Baabu yesterday said technical workers are hard to find in certain labour markets.He cited the construction industry, where technicians that used to be available are no longer present. &ldquo;Nowadays, you pay a carpenter between Sh2,000 to Sh2,500 per day, contrary to previous years where they would be paid Sh200 per day,&rdquo; Baabu said.He spoke at a Thanksgiving Day at Highlands Academy in Buuri subcounty, Meru. Baabu said students will get better defined career paths.He praised Education CS Fred Matiang&rsquo;i for improved management of last year&rsquo;s national examinations.